This article proposes a reflection on the broad media ostentation which causes vertigo in huge music events. This media ostentation prompts a profusion of fragmented visual and audio images in constant and intense movement which characterizes the environment of this kind of event. It also tries to better understand the nature of such big events, peculiar in urban cultures, as well as the enormous appeal they have among young audiences that look for large concentration of people and also an excess of such social situations.